					<p class="vertical-spacing"
						>Examples assume smallest viewport width of 320px, a tablet breakpoint at 768px, and a desktop
						breakpoint at 1024px.</p
					>
					<section class="vertical-spacing-150-percent" aria-describedby="example-1">
						<h3 id="example-1">Example 1 featuring two media queries</h3><span class="a-container"
							><a class="a" href="#example-1" aria-labelledby="example-1">#</a></span
						>
						<p class="vertical-spacing"
							>Suppose a <code class="inline-code">&lt;div&gt;</code> needs to be 90% wide below desktop breakpoint
							and 40% above that. Because you practice mobile-first approach, you start with:</p
						>
						<pre class="pre-block"><code class="block-code">div &lbrace;
    width: 90%;
&rbrace;</code></pre>
						<p class="vertical-spacing">and for desktop you add:</p>
						<pre class="pre-block"
							><code class="block-code">@media (min-width: 1024px) &lbrace;
    div &lbrace;
        width: 40%;
    &rbrace;
&rbrace;</code></pre
						>
						<p class="vertical-spacing"
							>You want to gradually transition between these two values so you reserve, let's say, the 900px -
							1024px range to smooth this out. You add another media query with the magic ü™Ñ <code
								class="inline-code">calc()</code
							> value that you generate using the <a class="link" href="#form">responsify form</a> below and you're
							done! üéâ</p
						>
						<pre class="pre-block"
							><code class="block-code">@media (min-width: 900px) and (max-width: 1023px) &lbrace;
    div &lbrace;
        width: calc(3716.129px - 322.903%); /* https://responsify.dev - parent lower bound: 900px; parent upper bound: 1024px; element lower bound: 90%; element upper bound: 40%; */
    &rbrace;
&rbrace;</code></pre
						>
						<p class="vertical-spacing"
							>Note the comment that accompanies <code class="inline-code">calc()</code> value. Preserving input
							values makes it easier to maintain the code.</p
						>
						<p class="vertical-spacing"
							>The comment also includes <code class="inline-code">https://responsify.dev</code> both as a reference
							for future maintainers and as a unique string you can match against when tracking down responsified
							values.</p
