    padding: 50px;
&rbrace;</code></pre>
						<p class="vertical-spacing">and for below desktop you add:</p>
						<pre class="pre-block"
							><code class="block-code">@media (max-width: 1023px) &lbrace;
    body &lbrace;
        padding: calc(-8.182px + 5.682vw); /* https://responsify.dev - viewport lower bound: 320px; viewport upper bound: 1024px; element lower bound: 10px; element upper bound: 50px; */
    &rbrace;
&rbrace;</code></pre
						>
						<p class="vertical-spacing"
							>I'm not a fan of using a <code class="inline-code">max-width</code> media query because it smells
							of a desktop-first approach üëé, but I've included it here for completeness' sake.</p
						>
					</section>

					<section class="vertical-spacing heading-container" aria-describedby="example-3">
						<h3 class="screen-reader-heading">Example 3 featuring max-height</h3>
						<h3 id="example-3" aria-hidden="true"
							>Example 3 featuring <code class="inline-code">max-height</code></h3
						><span class="a-container"><a class="a" href="#example-3" aria-labelledby="example-3">#</a></span>
						<p class="vertical-spacing"
							>You want the <code class="inline-code">&lt;header&gt;</code>'s <code class="inline-code"
								>height</code
							> to increase from 40px to 90px, and have it stay at 90px once it hits the desktop breakpoint.</p
						>
						<pre class="pre-block"
							><code class="block-code">header &lbrace;
    height: calc(17.273px + 7.102vw); /* https://responsify.dev - viewport lower bound: 320px; viewport upper bound: 1024px; element lower bound: 40px; element upper bound: 90px; */
    max-height: 90px;
&rbrace;</code></pre
						>
						<p class="vertical-spacing"
							>Without the <code class="inline-code">max-height</code> the <code class="inline-code"
								>&lt;header&gt;</code
							> would continue to grow in height with increase in viewport width. This approach removes the need
							for a media query üëç, but is limited to <code class="inline-code">width</code> and <code
								class="inline-code">height</code
							> as no other property has a corresponding <code class="inline-code">max-width</code> and <code
								class="inline-code">max-height</code
							>. üëé</p
						>
					</section>

					<section class="vertical-spacing heading-container" aria-describedby="example-4">
						<h3 class="screen-reader-heading">Example 4 featuring clamp()</h3>
						<h3 id="example-4" aria-hidden="true"
							>Example 4 featuring <code class="inline-code">clamp()</code></h3
						><span class="a-container"><a class="a" href="#example-4" aria-labelledby="example-4">#</a></span>
						<p class="vertical-spacing"
							>You want the <code class="inline-code">&lt;footer&gt;</code>'s <code class="inline-code"
								>margin-top</code
							> to be 20px below tablet breakpoint, 200px above desktop breakpoint, and increase from 2.6vw at tablet
							breakpoint (0.026 * 768px ‚âÖ 20px) to 19.5vw at desktop breakpoint (0.195 * 1024px ‚âÖ 200px).</p
						>
						<pre class="pre-block"
							><code class="block-code">footer &lbrace;
    margin-top: clamp(20px, calc(-515.482px + 69.87vw), 200px); /* https://responsify.dev - viewport lower bound: 768px; viewport upper bound: 1024px; element lower bound: 2.75vw; element upper bound: 19.53vw; */
&rbrace;</code></pre
						>
						<p class="vertical-spacing"
							>Responsify + <code class="inline-code">clamp()</code> is a powerful combination üí™ that allows you
							to mix and match units, something you can't do with responsify alone.</p
						>
					</section>

					<section class="vertical-spacing heading-container" aria-describedby="example-5">
						<h3 class="screen-reader-heading">Example 5 featuring ch and min()</h3>
						<h3 id="example-5" aria-hidden="true"
							>Example 5 featuring <code class="inline-code">ch</code> and <code class="inline-code"
								>min()</code
							></h3
						><span class="a-container"><a class="a" href="#example-5" aria-labelledby="example-5">#</a></span>
						<p class="vertical-spacing"
							>You want the <code class="inline-code">&lt;button&gt;</code>'s <code class="inline-code"
								>border-width</code
							> to increase from 1ch to 2ch, and have it stay at 2ch once it hits the desktop breakpoint. In this
							example let's say that the average character width is 13.65px.</p
						>
						<pre class="pre-block"
							><code class="block-code">button &lbrace;
    border-width: min(calc(0.545ch + 1.939vw), 2ch); /* https://responsify.dev - viewport lower bound: 320px; viewport upper bound: 1024px; element lower bound: 1ch; element upper bound: 2ch; "ch" width in pixels: 13.65; */
&rbrace;</code></pre
						>
						<p class="vertical-spacing"
							>By using <code class="inline-code">min()</code> you can do away with media query <em>and</em> you're
