				<section class="vertical-spacing-150-percent" aria-describedby="comparison">
					<h2 id="comparison">Comparison with CSS locks</h2><span class="a-container"
						><a class="a" href="#comparison" aria-labelledby="comparison">#</a></span
					>
					<p class="vertical-spacing"
						>CSS locks originated as <a
							class="link"
							href="https://tbrown.org/notes/2012/02/03/molten-leading-or-fluid-line-height/"
							target="_blank"
							rel="noopener noreferrer">Molten leading</a
						>. In the article that introduced the concept and in almost every example I came across CSS locks are
						used for controlling <code class="inline-code">line-height</code> and <code class="inline-code"
							>font-size</code
						>, even though it works with many CSS properties.</p
					>
					<p class="vertical-spacing"
						>CSS locks and responsify are based on fundamentally the same logic/math and as such share many
						similarities. They both:</p
					>
					<ul>
						<li>work with CSS properties that accept a <code class="inline-code">px</code> value,</li>
						<li
							>don't work with properties that accept keyword value like <code class="inline-code"
								>visibility</code
							>,</li
						>
						<li
							>don't work with properties that accept a unitless value like <code class="inline-code"
								>z-index</code
							>.</li
						>
					</ul>
					<p class="vertical-spacing"
						>There are also a few differences, most notable are listed in the following table.</p
					>
					<div class="table-container">
						<table class="vertical-spacing">
							<caption class="caption">CSS locks vs responsify</caption>
							<thead>
								<tr>
